    "body": "### Problem\r\n\r\nNvim running in the head-less mode, e.g., `nvim -l <lua script>` or `nvim --headless -c <cmds>` that writes some output, actually does not write into stdout (fd=1). All the messages are written to stderr (fd=2); see also #24184.\r\n\r\nThe current behavior is a bit unexpected, and there seems no easy way to make nvim behave as a standard CLI program. This hinders using `nvim -l` as a Lua scripting engine.\r\n\r\n### Steps to reproduce\r\n\r\nFor `nvim -l`:\r\n\r\n```bash\r\n# print to console\r\n❯❯❯ echo 'print(\"hi\")' | nvim --clean -i NONE -n -l -\r\nhi\r\n\r\n# try to redirect stdout, but nope\r\n❯❯❯ echo 'print(\"hi\")' | nvim --clean -i NONE -n -l - >/dev/null\r\nhi\r\n```\r\n\r\nSame for other messages: e.g. `echomsg`:\r\n\r\n```bash\r\n❯❯❯ nvim --clean -i NONE -n --headless -c 'echom \"echom\"' -c 'qa'  > /dev/null\r\nechom\r\n\r\n❯❯❯ nvim --clean -i NONE -n --headless -c 'echom \"echom\"' -c 'qa'  2> /dev/null\r\n```\r\n\r\n### Expected behavior\r\n\r\nNvim should write to stdout, so Nvim's stdout can be piped.\r\n\r\nError messages should be written to stderr.\r\n\r\n### Note (workaround)\r\n\r\nUsing direct stdio works. Because in Nvim, the global Lua function `_G.print()` and `:echom` are currently designed to write into some channel (messages), not to stdout.\r\n\r\n```\r\nio.stdout:write(\"hi\")\r\n```\r\n\r\nSo one could override `_G.print` with `io.stdout:write()`, but I think this could be a default behavior of `_G.print` in the headless mode -- at least for Lua.\r\n\r\nFor normal `:messages`, I'm not 100% sure whether it should directly write to `stdout`, but it may be reasonable to do so, so that one can read vim's message output in the headless mode -- without the use of additional APIs: e.g. `nvim_command_output()`.\r\n\r\n### Neovim version (nvim -v)\r\n\r\nNVIM v0.10.0-dev-2121+g06aebfa99  (in all NVIM versions so far)\r\n\r\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\r\n\r\nN/A\r\n\r\n### Operating system/version\r\n\r\nmacOS 14\r\n\r\n### Terminal name/version\r\n\r\nxterm\r\n\r\n### $TERM environment variable\r\n\r\nxterm-256color\r\n\r\n### Installation\r\n\r\nbuild from repo",
